metadata.name: Nullteilung #203
metadata.description:
Nullteilung is another exercise in suprematism and composition. Born from a series of exercises in subdevision and tesselation, it seeks to connect with the user through the creation of a sense of order and balance in the composition.

The term "Nullteilung" a German word that can be translated to "zero division" which is suggesative of the order and disorder paramount in the piece, working toward a goal of emotional and programmatic purity.

metadata.name: Meridian #9
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

'Meridian' attempts to capture some of the beauty and simplicity of Bauhaus design ideas. The addition of a line (or Meridian) to these simple shapes creates a colorful, striking design with an Art Deco vibe!

To download:
Click/tap 'open', then click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x2000px PNG.

metadata.name: MOUNTAINS #210
metadata.description:
"MOUNTAINS" is a work that belongs to the "FLUX Series", which utilizes the same techniques and processes as the previous work "FLUX". The shape in this piece is created by placing elements using noise and then performing recursive pixel operations on these elements.

The inspiration behind this work came from my continued sketches and studies of Flow Field, which led me to discover an expression of objects that seemed to be corroding. I believed that by applying this technique, I could create a realistic and vivid sculpture from a geometric shape.In this work, this corrosion treatment is applied to a geometric triangular shape of overlapping rectangles to form a realistic and dynamic mountain landscape.
It was as if geometric figures like Plato's "ideas" were materialized in the real world.

Additionally,  I was also inspired by the mountain views from my hometown at New Year's and by the manga background paintings of Yoshiharu Tsuge, who specializes in depicting villages with old hot springs.

It is possible to get a 5760 x 3240 px png file by right click save.

Please feel free to contact me if you have any inquiries.

Artwork by hasaqui, @hasaqui.
Made with p5js
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Resorting #118
metadata.description:
The idea of living within close proximity to nature has enticed people for centuries, especially for the ones used to living in bustling cities. Just picturing a cozy resort in the countryside, or playing music that resembles the feelings of holiday-making can drive us to go on a well-deserved vacation. Even when we don’t know where to, or whether we have the time or resources to slip out of our busy days, or even if that destination exists only in our imaginations. But when we do entertain ourselves with such ideas, we feel like we have taken a step to heal ourselves or to give our mind a worthy time out.

On the other hand, we have been living in human-focused settlements like cities for around 10,000 years, and we have all we need in an urban landscape, yet the idea of living in a secluded resort close to nature kept inviting us. This begs the question: were we supposed to live adjacent to nature to live well? Is it in our nature that we are wired to go back to the world beyond our doors? Or was it because we are aware of how big nature is, and how little time and resources we have to explore them all?

------------
Press [s] to save captured image
------------
It may take a few seconds to render, depending on the device.

created using WEBGL on p5.js
dirbots - Dec22

metadata.name: all that remains #83
metadata.description:
full title: all that remains / all that, remains / all, that remains

Parkinson's alters one's connection to the world they inhabit. I am very glad to be able to contribute to @Cure3Exhibition's fundraising towards @CureParkinsonsT's research for potential cures with my piece, "All that remains // all that, remains // all, that remains". A metaphor of one's world from what others see and from the 1st person perspective, where the self remains the same but its interface with the world is distorted.

One may question who is the person. Is it the person who sees herself, or is it how it expresses and relates to its environment? Mental / cognitive illnesses affect directly this notion of self, in dramatic ways for those affected and their loved ones. This piece explores both perspectives: the appearance from outside of what the person and their difficulty is, and the appearance of the person from inside, how one perceives herself. Not by creating a literal landscape of what being struck by Parkinson's means, but painting a metaphor of distorted worlds around a person, and allowing the experiencer to remove the distorted world and focus only on the person. How do we do this? Do we actually do this? Do we do this with people affected by illnesses? Do we realize we all live in a continuous spectrum of ability/disability, that we can all someday be subject to conditions that affect our position on this axis? 

I have had direct contact with relatives with Parkinson's disease, as well as other central nervous system / cognitive illnesses such as Alzheimer's disease. While these are different conditions, they end up affecting in similar ways to the person living through it and their environment. I am very grateful to Artwise Curators, Bonhams, Foteini Valeonti and Alex Estorick for the initiative, organization and inviting me, and Cure Parkinson's for all the effort towards finding potential cures. Your work is most needed.

100% of the primary sales and 100% of the royalties go to Cure Parkinson's for their efforts.

The artwork is interactive and allows the user to explore it. For instructions on how to do it, click on the artwork and press "i" while in live mode to download a text file with the instructions. Basic / most important interactions:

- Press "w" to switch the view between the distorted world / the world focused on the person.
- "i" to download the instructions.
- Press "s" to save the current image at the current resolution.
- Press "l" to obtain a different view.
- You can alter resolution, change the view / camera position / target, and other things with the provided controls.
- You can also specify a number of URL parameters, save the current view and other things. Please refer to the instructions.

The piece is graphics intensive and requires dedicated GPU to run properly. Tested on mid to high range GPUs on laptops and desktop computers. Will *not* work on most phones.

The piece might show a blank or noisy image if a distortion happens to fall very near to the camera. You can press "l" or explore with the provided commands, save the URL that defines the view and use it in future occasions.

Dedicated to everyone suffering from this condition, and to those working towards finding cures and improving patient's lives. Thanks.

metadata.name: Influence no.3:Auras #105
metadata.description:
The third set of the “Influence” series implies the creation of an abstract artwork based on algorithms and colors. Each of the color waves with different orientations next to each other creates an aura state that reminds of abstract acrylic paintings with spatula technique. Various densities and more than 12 color palettes have been used.

-----------

- Add &density=2 to 8 to the live view URL to render the image at higher resolution.

- Press ’s’ on the live mode to save the artwork.

note:
I highly recommend that you make sure you have enough RAM space and use the Chrome browser or Opera to view the animation in the best possible way. Rendering may take several minutes due to the high density of the artwork.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Illuminations #212
metadata.description:
Created for the FxHash Turns One week - Thank you FxHash for all the opportunities you have given generative artists and collectors, and thank you to everyone who makes, and collects, the great art here. Here are a few celebratory generative effects which come from my 2022 experiments on random walks through color and space.

There are 5 different burst patterns (Whirligig, Sky Ripple, Confetti, Classic, Sparkler) and the Cocktail type brings them all together (somewhat chaotically)

To continue with the display after it stops press c

To switch to tranquil mode press t - You will want to try this out when you have a minute

To switch back to live mode press v

To stop the display process press x

To save a 2800x2800 jpg press s

Made with p5.js - all proceeds and royalties assigned to the Processing Foundation (who also deserve a big thank you)

This work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International License.

metadata.name: 🔸WOMAN 🔹LIFE🔹 FREEDOM🔸 #730
metadata.description:
📅 To be recorded in history as the first event-based stamp collection of generative art on the blockchain. 

🟩🟩🟩🟩🟩
⬜️⬜️⬜️⬜️⬜️
🟥🟥🟥🟥🟥

🔆The people of my country – Iran - have been chanting three words for several days: 🔸Woman🔸🔹Life🔸🔸Freedom🔸.

🟢For over forty years, we have fought for these beautiful words. Today, our most basic human rights are being ignored in Iran, and we fight for them every day. In my land, women fight and die but do not accept humiliation. Women and men stand shoulder to shoulder and fight together.

🟢I published this collection of 1401 generative tokens to show my support for the people of Iran. 401 tokens are reserved for other known supporters of this cause, and 1000 tokens are free to mint.

🟢All my works about Iran's freedom are royalty-free and will always be. Due to fxhash's limitation on royalty selection, I have selected it all for the minter.
